Here is the LaTeX code that uses the TikZ library to recreate the quantum circuit diagram shown in the image:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{quantikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{quantikz}
    \lstick{$ $} & \gate{R_y(\theta_1)} & \ctrl{1} & \targ{}  & \ctrl{1} & \targ{}  & \qw \slice[dashed]{$\times D$} \\
    \lstick{$ $} & \gate{R_y(\theta_2)} & \targ{}  & \ctrl{-1} & \targ{}  & \ctrl{-1} & \qw                         \\
    \lstick{$ $} & \gate{R_y(\theta_3)} & \ctrl{1} & \targ{}  & \ctrl{1} & \targ{}  & \qw                         \\
    \lstick{$ $} & \gate{R_y(\theta_4)} & \targ{}  & \ctrl{-1} & \targ{}  & \ctrl{-1} & \qw
\end{quantikz}

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **`quantikz` Library**: This is a TikZ library specifically designed for drawing quantum circuit diagrams.
- **`\gate{R_y(\theta_i)}`**: Represents a quantum gate, specifically a rotation around the y-axis by an angle \(\theta_i\) applied to the \(i\)-th qubit.
- **`\ctrl{}` and `\targ{}`**: These commands represent control and target qubits for CNOT gates.
- **`\qw`**: Stands for "quantum wire," indicating the continuation of a qubit line.
- **`\lstick{}`**: Used to label the left side of the circuit (though in this example, labels are left empty).
- **`\slice[dashed]{$\times D$}`**: Adds a dashed vertical line with a label indicating that the enclosed layer can be repeated \(D\) times.

This code replicates the entangling ansatz circuit diagram, with the inner dashed box indicating a repeatable layer structure.
